Data Dictionary: Number of probable cases with a specimen collection date. Probable cases are individuals with a positive antigen test for COVID-19 and no positive molecular test. The case classification can change to confirmed based on subsequent testing. The case is recorded to the day with the earliest specimen collection date of a positive test, regardless of test type.

Number of confirmed cases with a specimen collection date. Confirmed cases are individuals with a positive molecular test for COVID-19. The case is recoded to the day with the earliest specimen collection date of a positive test, regardless of test type.

Number of confirmed and probable cases with a specimen collection date. The case is recorded to the day with the earliest specimen collection date of a positive test, regardless of test type.The 14-day case rate is calculated as the sum of total cases over the past 14 days divided by the population, then multiplied by 100,000.

Number of hospitalizations among confirmed and probable cases with an admission date.The 7-day hospitalization rate is calculated as the sum of hospitalizations over the past 7 days divided by the population, then multiplied by 100,000.

Number of deaths among confirmed and probable cases with a specimen collection date. The death is recorded to the day with the earliest specimen collection date of a positive test, regardless of test type.The 7-day death rate is calculated as the sum of deaths over the past 7 days divided by the population, then multiplied by 100,000.
All cases from the past 8 days may not yet be reported. It takes up to 8 days from specimen collection date for DOH to receive 90% of reported cases.
All hospitalizations from the last 8 days may not yet be reported. It typically takes 8 days for 90% of COVID-19 hospitalizations to be reported in our data.
All deaths from the past 32 days may not yet be reported. It generally takes 32 days from the earliest speciment collection date to the date of a COVID-related death certificate is received.

Population for the state or county from the single year 2020 intercensal estimate from Washington State Office of Financial Management. Estimates can be found at https://ofm.wa.gov/washington-data-research/population-demographics/population-estimates/april-1-official-population-estimates.
